"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">35</A>
Probably a collection of love stories, the scenes of which were laid in Miletus. Of its author, who flourished perhaps in the second century <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>, almost nothing is known.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note36" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Crassus*.html#ref36
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">36</A>
In the fable of the two wallets, which everyone carries, one in front containing his neighbour's faults, which are therefore always before his eyes; and one behind containing his own faults, which therefore he never sees.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note37" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Crassus*.html#ref37
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">37</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Crassus*.html#21.6
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">chapter xxi.6</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note38" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Crassus*.html#ref38
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">38</A>
Pentheus, king of Thebes, the son of Agave, refused to recognize the divinity of Dionysus, whereupon the god infuriated the women, and Agave killed her own son. She appears in the <I>Bacchae</I> with his head in her hand, exulting over the death of the supposed wild beast.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note39" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Crassus*.html#ref39
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">39</A>
A poet competing at the Athenian City Dionysia exhibited three tragedies and a satyric drama, "the four plays being performed in succession in the course of the same day."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note40" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Crassus*.html#ref40
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">40</A>
38 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> <I>Cf.</I> Plutarch's
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Antony*.html#34
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Antony</I>, xxxiv.1</A>. According to
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cassius_Dio/49*.html#21.2
	"TARGET="Cassius_Dio_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Dio,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Dio Cassius, <SPAN CLASS="small">XLIX</SPAN>.21</A>, Pacorus fell on the same day on which Crassus had been slain fifteen years before.



	<HR CLASS="endnotes"><A ID="endnotes_T"></A>
	<H2>
Thayer's Notes:
	</H2>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Maidikou" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Crassus*.html#ref:Maidikou
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a</A>
An alternate manuscript reading or emendation has been pointed out to me here by a Bulgarian correspondent; instead of <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">ἀνὴρ Θρᾷξ τοῦ Νομαδικοῦ γένους</SPAN>, at least one edition out there (I'm awaiting a better citation) apparently reads <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">ἀνὴρ Θρᾷξ τοῦ <SPAN CLASS="emend">Μαιδικοῦ</SPAN> γένους</SPAN>: instead of "Nomadic stock", "Medic stock".


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Vargonteius" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Crassus*.html#ref:Vargonteius
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">b</A>
Thanks to Prof. John Morgan of the University of Delaware for restoring the Loeb translation to the correct reading. The Greek text gives the name as <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">Βαργοντήιος</SPAN> (Vargonteios).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:halfbreed_Greeks" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Crassus*.html#ref:halfbreed_Greeks
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">c</A>
Descendants no doubt of Alexander's army, which had briefly held the region in the 4c: these Asian Greeks are known to have maintained their identity for many generations.



